In [4]:
def clean_text(text):
    text = text.lower()
    text = re.sub(r'[^a-z\s]', '', text)
    return ' '.join(word for word in text.split() if word not in stopwords)
In [5]:
# STEP 4: Read .doc and .docx
def read_doc(file_path):
    try:
        word = client.Dispatch("Word.Application")
        word.Visible = False
        doc = word.Documents.Open(file_path)
        full_text = doc.Content.Text
        doc.Close()
        word.Quit()
        return full_text
    except Exception as e:
        print(f"❌ Error reading .doc: {file_path} — {e}")
        return None

def read_docx(file_path):
    try:
        doc = Document(file_path)
        return '\n'.join([para.text for para in doc.paragraphs])
    except Exception as e:
        print(f"❌ Error reading .docx: {file_path} — {e}")
        return None

# STEP 5: Walk folders and collect data
data = []

for folder in os.listdir(data_path):
    folder_path = os.path.join(data_path, folder)
    if os.path.isdir(folder_path):
        for file in os.listdir(folder_path):
            file_path = os.path.join(folder_path, file)
            print("🔍 Reading:", file)
            try:
                if file.lower().endswith(".doc"):
                    text = read_doc(file_path)
                elif file.lower().endswith(".docx"):
                    text = read_docx(file_path)
                else:
                    continue

                if text:
                    cleaned = clean_text(text)
                    data.append({'text': cleaned, 'label': folder})
            except Exception as e:
                print(f"❌ Failed reading {file_path}: {e}")

print("✅ Total resumes loaded:", len(data))

# === Top 10 Words Per Job Role ===
print("\nTop 10 Words per Job Role:")
top_words = {}
for label in df['label'].unique():
    vec = CountVectorizer(max_features=10, stop_words='english')
    vec.fit(df[df['label'] == label]['text'])
    top_words[label] = vec.get_feature_names_out()
    print(f"{label}: {top_words[label]}")

# === Function to extract skills from resume text ===
def extract_skills(text, skill_list):
    text = str(text).lower()
    return [skill for skill in skill_list if skill in text]

# === Apply skill extraction ===
df['skills'] = df['text'].apply(lambda x: extract_skills(x, common_skills))

# === Flatten all skills into one list ===
from collections import Counter
all_skills = [skill for sublist in df['skills'] for skill in sublist]
skill_counts = Counter(all_skills)

# === Bar Chart of Top 20 Skills ===
top_skills = skill_counts.most_common(20)
skills_df = pd.DataFrame(top_skills, columns=['Skill', 'Frequency'])

plt.title('Top 20 Skills in Resumes')

plt.xlabel('Skill')
plt.tight_layout()

In [37]:
# === Step 10: Predict on New Resume Text ===
def predict_job_role(resume_text):
    resume_text = resume_text.lower()  # Optional cleaning
    vectorized = tfidf.transform([resume_text])
    pred_encoded = model.predict(vectorized)
    pred_label = label_encoder.inverse_transform(pred_encoded)
    return pred_label[0]

# 🔍 Example usage
sample_resume = """
Proficient in Python, SQL, and Tableau. Experience working with data pipelines and dashboards.
Worked on machine learning models and deployed in AWS cloud.
"""
print("Predicted Job Role:", predict_job_role(sample_resume))

Predicted Job Role: React Developer
